===Etymology===
ca. 1557; variant of {{term|yaught|lang=en}}, earlier {{term|yeaghe|lang=en||light, fast-sailing ship}}, from obsolete {{etyl|nl|en}} {{term|jaghte|jaght(e)|lang=nl|hunt}} (modern {{term|jacht|lang=nl}}), short for {{term|jaghtschip|lang=nl}}, {{term|jageschip|lang=nl||light sailing vessel, fast pirate ship}}, literally, "pursuit ship", compound of {{term|jagen|lang=nl||to hunt, chase}} and {{term|schip|lang=nl||ship}} (see [[ship]]), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|jagōnan|lang=gem-pro}} (cf. West Frisian {{term|jeie|lang=fy}}, German {{term|jagen|lang=de}}, Swedish {{term|jaga|lang=sv}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|yegʰo-|lang=ine-pro}} (compare Irish {{term|éad|lang=ga||jealousy}}, Russian {{term|ярый|tr=âryj||furious}}, Albanian {{term|gjah|lang=sq||hunt}}, Ancient Greek {{term|ζητέω|tr=zētéō||to search, seek|lang=grc}}, Sanskrit {{term|यवन|tr=yāvana||barbarian; agressor|lang=sa}}, {{term|यत्न||zeal|tr=yātna|lang=sa}}).

In the 16th century the Dutch built light, fast ships to chase the ships of pirates and smugglers from the coast. The ship was introduced to England in 1660 when the Dutch East India Company presented one to King Charles II, who used it as a pleasure boat, after which it was copied by British shipbuilders as a pleasure craft for wealthy gentlemen.

